title: ‘Very impressive’: Ray Hadley lauds Angus Taylor’s first week leading the Liberal Party
description: Veteran radio host Ray Hadley lauds Angus Taylor’s first week as Liberal Party Leader.

title: 'Bondi: A Timeline of Terror' airs Tuesday at 7:30 PM
description: Sky News host Sharri Markson shares a sneak peek into her new documentary “Bondi: A Timeline of Terror,” airing Tuesday at  7:30 PM.  “One thing that emerged in many of the interviews I did is the sense that this was not a surprise,” Ms Markson said.  “And that some of those impacted by Bondi had actually been fighting against hatred against the Jewish community over the past two years.  ​“It's incredibly powerful, it's very moving, and I highly recommend you watch it.”

title: NSW confirms ‘months’ of planning with Albanese government to repatriate ISIS brides
description: Sky News host Sharri Markson says NSW Premier Chris Minns confirmed the state had been working with the Albanese government for “months” to repatriate the ISIS brides.  “This comes despite the prime minister and home affairs minister repeatedly denying that they've in any way assisted the cohort,” Ms Markson said.  “The Albanese government was aware of the ISIS group's return; they didn't block it when they could have, and they were planning to help them after they were back here on Australian soil.”

title: Inside look into hard-hitting Bondi terror attack documentary
description: Sky News host Sharri Markson reveals her powerful new documentary exposing the rise of antisemitism that ultimately led to the Bondi terror attack.  Ms Markson’s documentary, “Bondi: A Timeline of Terror,” will premiere at 7:30 PM on Tuesday.  “People were worried about this, and they are angry at the prime minister for his lack of action,” Ms Markson said.  “We interviewed 57 witnesses, survivors, heroes, victims, and family members of people killed.  “They want Australians to know what happened.”

title: New details emerge on third alleged Trump assassination attempt at Mar-a-Lago
description: Sky News contributor Kosha Gada discusses new details surrounding the third assassination attempt against US President Donald Trump, in which an armed man was shot dead by Secret Service agents at the Mar-a-Lago resort.  “He had a can of gasoline, alongside the gun. When authorities told him to stand down, he reportedly put the can of gasoline down but aimed the firearms at them,” Ms Gada told Sky News host Sharri Markson.  “That is what led to them reacting with lethal force.”

title: US-Iran tensions ‘escalate’ as envoy warns of nuclear threat
description: Sky News contributor Kosha Gada says tensions between America and Iran are "escalating" as US Special Envoy Steve Witkoff has warned Iran could have nuclear bomb making material within a week.  “The fleet has been moved for a long time to that region, and that is President Trump’s signature style, sort of showing force, doing a bit of sabre-rattling,” Ms Gada told Sky News host Sharri Markson.  “It seems like we’re closer than we have ever been.”

title: Australian teaching standards at risk as school results over last decade decline
description: Sky News host Caleb Bond details how Australian teaching standards are at risk, as school results over the last decade have steadily declined.   “Something that we should not get over … is the quality of our teachers,” Mr Bond said.  “You look at NAPLAN results, and other school results over the last decade at least, and it will show that we are on the decline, we are being beaten in so many categories.”

title: Andrew scandal a ‘headache’ for King Charles
description: TalkTV host Mark Dolan calls the ongoing criminal investigation against former prince Andrew a “car crash in slow motion”.  “This could take years, so the problem you’ve got is the headlines aren't going to go away, the scandal isn't going to go away,” Mr Dolan told Sky News host Paul Murray.  “In terms of any new developments, well, a fresh headache for the King because there are now questions being asked about how much he knew.  “He’s going to have to demonstrate that he knew nothing about what his brother was up to.”

title: Melbourne City Council attends conference in support of UN nuclear non-proliferation treaty
description: Sky News host James Macpherson details how the Melbourne City Council is attending a conference to move a motion in support of the UN Treaty on the Prohibition of Nuclear Weapons.   “Local government, it’s meant to be about rates, roads, and rubbish, right?” Mr Macpherson said.  “Well, not if you’re a Melbourne City councillor … instead of focusing on the things they’re elected to do, they’re attending a conference to move a motion on the support of the UN treaty on the prohibition of nuclear weapons.”

title: New travel rules for politicians released after ‘minister for freebies’ Anika Wells scandal
description: Sky News host Paul Murray says the Albanese government enjoys spending taxpayers' dollars.    “You remember how angry you were … that no matter how hard you have worked in your life … that when the minister for freebies Anika Wells was caught, there was nothing to see here, the rules couldn’t possibly change,” Mr Murray said.  “When she, of course, as both minister for communications … sports minister … you are paying for the privilege of her being there.”

title: Donald Trump intends to use military assets against Iran as tensions escalate
description: Sky News Political Contributor Chris Uhlmann comments on the US ramping up its military presence in the Middle East amid escalating tensions between Iran and the US.  “We don’t move those sorts of assets into place without intending to use them, I'm pretty sure that Donald Trump intends to use them, I’m sure that the Israeli government’s pushing them to use them,” Mr Uhlmann told Sky News host Peta Credlin.  “The question is, how, and how big a strike might come? … you assume that Benjamin Netanyahu is saying to Donald Trump, you cannot trust anything they say.”

title: Coalition facing an ‘existential crisis’ and may be ‘annihilated’ in South Australia
description: Sky News Political Contributor Chris Uhlmann says the Coalition is facing an “existential crisis”, claiming it could be “annihilated” in South Australia.   “Let’s face it, the Coalition faces an existential crisis at the moment,” Mr Uhlmann told Sky News host Peta Credlin.  “It’ll be tested in South Australia; it may well be annihilated in South Australia.”

title: ‘Get your popcorn out’: House Republicans plan to grill Clintons over Epstein ties
description: Sky News host Danica De Giorgio discusses Bill and Hillary Clinton’s upcoming deposition over their ties with Jeffrey Epstein.   “Get your popcorn out because Bill and Hillary Clinton, they’re going to face the US Congress to outline their ties to Jeffrey Epstein,” Ms De Giorgio said.  “I don’t know about you, but I can’t wait to hear the former president explain this infamous photo in the late pedophile’s hot tub.  “This is going to be interesting.”

title: ‘Does not want voter ID’: Mamdani’s hypocrisy on full display with snow shovelling plea
description: The Tudor Dixon Podcast host Tudor Dixon reacts to New York City Mayor Zohran Mamdani requiring people to have ID to sign up as snow shovellers.   “The man who does not want voter ID is going to require you to have two forms of ID … you also have to have copies of those IDs,” Ms Dixon told Sky News host Danica De Giorgio.  “How is this possible? I mean, this just proves that their theory that you should not have to have an ID to vote is totally bunk.  “As soon as he did this, every Republican looked at this and said pass the Save Act right now.”

title: ‘Surprise’: CNN given 'reality check' over Trump’s universal tariff hike
description: Sky News host Danica De Giorgio reacts to footage on CNN in which Business and Politics correspondent Vanessa Yurkevich says US President Donald Trump can implement his recently proposed tariffs.  “Donald Trump is now planning to hike that universal tariff rate from 10 per cent to 15 per cent,” Ms De Giorgio said.   “Surprise, what a breakthrough, yes, he can indeed.”
